    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA — SpaceX S-1 Disclosure\n\n## Exact Figures for All Periods Presented\n\n| Period | Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA |\n|---|---|\n| **FY2023** (Year Ended Dec. 31, 2023) | **$1,602 million** |\n| **FY2024** (Year Ended Dec. 31, 2024) | **$3,849 million** |\n| **FY2025** (Year Ended Dec. 31, 2025) | **$7,168 million** |\n| **Q1 2025** (Three Months Ended Mar. 31, 2025) | **$1,618 million** |\n| **Q1 2026** (Three Months Ended Mar. 31, 2026) | **$2,087 million** |\n\n### Year-over-year changes explicitly stated in the filing:\n- **2024 vs. 2023:** Increased $2,247 million (from $1,602M to $3,849M)\n- **2025 vs. 2024:** Increased $3,319 million (from $3,849M to $7,168M)\n- **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** Increased $469 million (from $1,618M to $2,087M)\n- The filing notes the Connectivity segment became Segment Adjusted EBITDA positive on a sustained basis **beginning in 2023**.\n\n---\n\n## How Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA Is Defined\n\nSegment Adjusted EBITDA is disclosed as a **non-GAAP financial measure**. The filing directs readers to the section titled *"Management\'s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations—Non-GAAP Financial Measures"* and describes it as reconciled to **segment income (loss) from operations**, which is identified as "the most directly comparable GAAP measure."\n\nFrom the reconciliation tables, the measure is constructed as follows:\n\n| Line Item | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Income from operations | $469 | $2,006 | $4,423 | $1,033 | $1,188 |\n| **Add:** Depreciation and amortization | 884 | 1,508 | 2,376 | 510 | 783 |\n| **Add:** Share-based compensation | 249 | 296 | 369 | 75 | 116 |\n| **Add:** Restructuring charges | — | — | — | — | — |\n| **Add:** Impairment | — | 39 | — | — | — |\n| **= Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$1,602** | **$3,849** | **$7,168** | **$1,618** | **$2,087** |\n\n*(All figures in millions)*\n\nIn summary, Segment Adjusted EBITDA = Income (loss) from operations + Depreciation and amortization + Share-based compensation + Restructuring charges + Impairment. Notably, for the Connectivity segment, restructuring charges and impairments were zero or negligible across all presented periods, meaning the measure is primarily operating income plus D&A and stock-based compensation.\n\n---\n\n## Is Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA Described as the Primary Internal Cash Source?\n\n**Yes — the filing explicitly frames it in this role within the capital allocation narrative.** Specifically, the S-1 states:\n\n> *"We invested in our Connectivity segment as we generated Segment Adjusted EBITDA from our Space segment, along with additional equity capital that we raised externally, creating a segment that generates predictable and recurring revenue from consumer, enterprise, and government customers."*\n\nThis passage establishes a sequential funding model: Space segment Adjusted EBITDA helped fund the build-out of Connectivity, and Connectivity has now matured into the company\'s primary cash-generating engine. The filing further reinforces this by noting:\n\n- The Connectivity segment generated **$7,168 million** in Segment Adjusted EBITDA in 2025 — by far the largest positive contributor among the three reportable segments (vs. Space at $653M and AI at $(1,237)M).\n- The company describes its **primary sources of liquidity** as "cash flows generated from operations" alongside balance-sheet cash and marketable securities ($15,852M cash and $7,823M short-term marketable securities as of March 31, 2026).\n- The Connectivity segment\'s growth is attributed to "expanding the scale and efficiency of our LEO satellite constellations and our highly verticalized supply chain, which has delivered major cost reductions in user terminal production."\n\nWhile the filing does not use the exact phrase "primary internal cash source" as a formal label for Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA, the capital allocation discussion makes clear that Connectivity is the dominant positive EBITDA contributor and the segment whose operating cash generation supports continued investment across the business — including the capital-intensive AI segment, which is expected to require "a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA."',
